## Audience reflexes (palette/category traps to reject)

What would a stranger guess about this category from a typical site? List the visual reflexes the design must NOT default to.

For example, for a pediatric dentist:
- Reflex: navy + sky blue + coral + cartoon tooth + Fraunces serif → REJECT
- Reflex: blue + white + smiling stock-photo dentist → REJECT
- Reflex: bright + playful + Comic Sans-adjacent → REJECT

## Success criterion (visual)

What does "this design works" look like? Not "users convert." Not "passes accessibility." A specific visual moment. "When a homeowner shows their spouse, the spouse says 'wait, scroll back to that aerial shot'" or "when a Signal Works prospect lands, they immediately ask 'who built this?'"

## Failure mode to avoid

The one thing that would make this design wrong for the brand. "If this looks like every other AI-built dental site, it failed." "If the visitor cannot tell within 5 seconds that this is not Inter and a card grid, it failed."
